'''Arignotus''' ({{lang-grc|Ἀρίγνωτος}}) was a [[Pythagoreanism|Pythagorean]] in the time of [[Lucian]] -- that is, the 2nd century CE -- who was renowned for his wisdom. and had the surname of ἱερός ("the holy").<ref>[[Lucian]], ''Philopseudeis'' c. 29, &c.</ref> He is described as telling a story of a time he exorcised a demon that was haunting a home.<ref name="magic"/>
Arignotus is described as shabby and dirty, wearing his hair long and having a grave expression. Modern scholars have suggested that there was not a historical person with this name, but that "Arignotus" represents a popularly known type of the time, and is essentially a stand-in for [[Pythagoras]] himself.<ref name="magic">{{cite book | last =Dickie | first =Matthew | title =Magic and Magicians in the Greco-Roman World | publisher =[[Psychology Press]] | date =2003 | pages = 196,204,208 | language =English | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=TgfLYOZPHSMC | isbn = 9780415311298 | accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref> Other scholars disagree with this hypothesis.<ref>{{cite book | last =Ogden | first =Daniel | editor-last1=Morgan | editor-first1=John Robert | editor-last2=Jones | editor-first2=Meriel | title =Philosophical Presences in the Ancient Novel | chapter=The Love of Wisdom and the Love of Lies: The Philosophers and Philosophical Voices of Lucian's Philopseudes | publisher =[[Barkhuis]] | series =Ancient narrative | volume =10 | date =2007 | pages =196 | language =English | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=DyKsnRoCbq4C | isbn = 9789077922378 | issn = 1574-5066 | accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref>
There is an unrelated, otherwise unknown Arignotus mentioned in [[Aeschines]]'s speech ''[[Against Timarchus]]''.<ref>{{cite book | last =Aeschines | authorlink =Aeschines | editor-last1=Wolpert | editor-first1=Andrew | editor-last2=Kapparis | editor-first2=Konstantinos | title =Legal Speeches of Democratic Athens: Sources for Athenian History | publisher =[[Hackett Publishing]] | date =2011 | pages =257 | language =English | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=jctgDwAAQBAJ | isbn = 9781603846066 | accessdate=2018-10-19}}</ref>
