{{Subud}}
'''Latihan''' (from Indonesian ''latihan kejiwaan''; "spiritual exercise") is a form of spiritual  practice. It is the principal practice of the [[Subud]] organization.{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=268}}{{sfn|Chryssides|1999|p=262}}

==Origin==
The origin of the practice is associated with Javanese [[kebatinan|"kebatinan" or "kejawen" tradition]].{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=272}}

==The practice==
''Latihan kejiwaan'' (or simply ''latihan'') means "spiritual exercise", or "training of the spirit".{{sfn|Chryssides|1999|p=261}} This exercise is not thought about, learned or trained for; it is unique for each person and the ability to 'receive' it is passed on by being in the presence of another person who aready practises it at the 'opening'. About twice a week, Subud members go to a local center to participate in a group latihan, men and women separately.{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=269–270}} The experience takes place in a room or a hall with open space. After a period of sitting quietly, the members are typically asked to stand and relax by a 'helper', who then announces the start of the exercise.{{sfn|Chryssides|1999|p=263}}{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=270}}

Practitioners are advised to surrender to the Divine and follow 'what arises from within', not expecting anything in advance. One is recommended not to focus on any image or recite any mantra, nor to mix the exercise with other activities like meditation or use of drugs, but simply to intend to surrender to the Divine or the will of God. (The term "God" is used here with a broad and inclusive intention. An individual is at liberty to substitute interpretations that they feel more in tune with.) One is not to pay attention to others in the room, each of whom is doing his or her own latihan.{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=270}} During the exercise, practitioners may find that, in terms of physical and emotional expression, they involuntarily move, make sounds, walk around, dance, jump, skip, laugh, cry or whatever.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=122}}{{sfn|Chryssides|1999|p=263}} The experience varies greatly for different people, but the practitioner is always wholly conscious throughout and free to stop the exercise at any time.

Outwardly the exercise often manifests as physical movement and vocal activity that vary greatly both over time and between individuals.{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=270}} It proceeds spontaneously, involving neither teacher nor method,{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=268}} being unstructured except for basic rules relating to group practice.{{sfn|Chryssides|1999|p=263}}

Personal capacity to engage in ''latihan'' the first time, in what is called the "opening", is said to be transmitted by the presence of experienced practitioners.{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=268}} It usually entails an attitude of patience and trust, typically with some preparatory relaxation of thoughts and feelings,{{sfn|Chryssides|1999|p=152}} and involves the whole human being, not just body, emotions, mind or any other single facet.{{sfn|Geels|1997|p=148}}

It is regarded by practitioners as being of spiritual or psychological benefit, depending on personal interpretation and individual experience{{sfn|Geels|1997|p=148-160, 196-205}}{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=122}}{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=263}} though apparently it does not affect all practitioners and may affect some detrimentally.{{sfn|Briedis|2009|p=228}}{{sfn|Geels|1997|p=150, 164}} Many practitioners see ''latihan'' as a way of direct access to a [[mystical experience]] that is compatible with a busy modern lifestyle.

===Use in Subud===
{{Main|Subud}}

While the opinions of [[Subud]]'s founder are often cited among its members,{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=270}} the organization officially endorses no doctrine regarding latihan's nature or benefits.{{sfn|Hunt|2003|p=122}} Practitioners tend to agree that the exercise is best experienced with minimal theorizing or mental imagery.{{sfn|Chryssides|1999|p=150}}

Although ''latihan'' can be practiced alone,{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=270}} [[Subud]] arranges regular practice in group settings. Normally sessions are held two or three times a week and last thirty minutes, with the two sexes segregated.{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=269-270}} Subud offers formal pragmatic, preliminary advice in relation to commencing the practice.{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=270}} Non-members are not allowed to witness Subud ''latihan'' sessions as they are considered private.{{sfn|Webb|1995|p=270}}

Subud's founder speculated that the spontaneous movements which characterise ''latihan'' are similar in character to early meetings of the [[Religious Society of Friends]] which gave rise to the name [[Quakers]].{{refn|group=note|It also resembles reports of followers of [[H. W. L. Poonja]] and [[Andrew Cohen (spiritual teacher)|Andrew Cohen]], who also report spontaneous awakening while [[Satsang|being in their presence]].}}

=== Raja Yoga ===
The use of ''latihan'' is also included by Vladimir Antonov in his program of [[Rāja yoga|raja yoga]].<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://autobiography.swami-center.org/yoga-and-evolution.shtml
| title = Raja Yoga and Buddhi Yoga: Their Place in the Evolution
| website = autobiography.swami-center.org
| access-date = 2016-02-26
}}</ref> He states that [[Rāja yoga|raja yoga]] is a stage of spiritual work aimed at, among other things, purifying the body from coarse energies, and refining oneself as a consciousness to the level of being able to experience [[samadhi]] (the bliss of contact with God).<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://encyclopedia-of-religion.org/raja_yoga.html
| title = Raja Yoga
| website = encyclopedia-of-religion.org
| access-date = 2016-02-25
}}</ref>

The method of ''latihan'' consists in feeling the Holy Spirit (Te, Brahmin, etc.) above oneself as Living Light—and asking It to flow through one's body from above. By surrendering to this flow, the body can start making spontaneous movements with the arms, hands, etc.<ref>{{Cite book
| title = Spiritual Practices
| last = Antonov
| first = Vladimir
| publisher = iUniverse, Inc.
| year = 2002
| isbn = 0-595-27699-7
| location = 2021 Pine Lake Rd, Suite 100, Lincoln, NE 68512
| pages = 63, 64
}}</ref> ''Latihan'' is sometimes referred to by the name 'spontaneous dance', due to the movements of the body that can happen while surrendering to the flow of light.<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://ecopsychology.swami-center.org/latihan-holy-spirit.shtml
| title = Latihan. Baptism in the Holy Spirit
| website = ecopsychology.swami-center.org
| access-date = 2016-02-25
}}</ref>

''Latihan'' can also be classified as a meditation of the '[[Laya yoga|Laya]]' type, i.e. as a means of dissolving oneself in Living God.<ref>{{Cite web
| url = http://encyclopedia-of-religion.org/laya_yoga.html
| title = Laya Yoga
| website = encyclopedia-of-religion.org
| access-date = 2016-02-26
}}</ref>

==Active meditation==
The method was later adopted by [[Osho (Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh)]], who made use of many spiritual methods. He viewed ''latihan'' as potentially beneficial, capable of cleansing the mind, yet incomplete and potentially dangerous to mental health since it involved surrender of self-control.<ref name="oshosearch.net">{{cite web|url=http://oshosearch.net/Convert/Articles_Osho/Sermons_in_Stones/Osho-Sermons-in-Stones-00000021.html|title=Osho Sermons in Stones: This too will pass...|website=oshosearch.net|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> He therefore incorporated it as a stage of longer "active meditations", advocating the maintenance of a "witnessing consciousness", following ''latihan'' with a period of complete rest and preceding it with one of several techniques intended to promote an [[Autohypnosis|autohypnotic trance]], and further recommended that, when practising in groups, both sexes should practise together.<ref name="oshosearch.net"/> Preliminary methods used include listening to quiet music,<ref>http://www.oshoteachings.com/osho-devavani-meditation-osho-devavani-active-meditation/</ref> or else a breathing exercise intended to increase blood [[carbon dioxide]] levels followed by fifteen minutes looking at a [[strobe]] light while listening to music, both of these running at seven times the rate of the heart-beat in order to create an [[Brainwave entrainment|entrainment]] to [[alpha wave]] brain-state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oshoteachings.com/osho-active-meditations-osho-gourishankar-meditation/|title=Site Unavailable|website=oshoteachings.com|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> It may also be followed by a form of wordless prayer. He agreed that it was easiest to learn in the presence of someone already experienced in the method.<ref>http://www.messagefrommasters.com/Psychic-World/osho_latihan_mahamudra.htm</ref>

