{{Orphan|date=May 2015}}
[[File:Abou Yaareb Marzouki, Tunisia 2012.jpg|thumb|Mohamed Habib Marzouki in 2012]] '''Mohamed Habib Marzouki''' ({{lang-ar|محمد الحبيب المرزوقي}}; born 29 March 1947) is a Tunisian academic, philosopher and politician. He was a member of the [[Constituent Assembly of Tunisia|Constituent Assembly]] from 22 November 2011 to 6 March 2013.
==Early life and education == He was born in [[Ferryville, French Protectorate of Tunisia]]. The thirteenth in a family of fifteen children, he obtained a philosophy degree at the [[Sorbonne University]] in 1972. He taught at the [[University of Tunis]] between 1980 and 2006 and at the International Islamic University of Malaysia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ville-tunisie.com/tunisie/%20international%20l%E2%80%99agence.html?start=60|title=International L’agence|publisher=Ville-tunisie.com|accessdate=3 May 2015|language=French}}</ref>
==Political career== He was elected to the [[Constituent Assembly of Tunisia|Constituent Assembly]] as a representative of the Islamist party [[Ennahda]] for the district of Tunis on 23 October 2011, and was subsequently appointed advisor to the Culture and the Education minister. He later resigned from the assembly on 6 March 2013, and returned to the teaching of philosophy. He also translated several philosophical works to Arabic, including texts by [[Pierre Duhem]], [[Gaston Bachelard]] and [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-croix.com/Actualite/Monde/Abou-Yaareb-Marzouki-l-islamiste-moderne-tunisien-2013-10-23-1049739|title=Abou Yaareb Marzouki, l’" islamiste moderne " tunisien|publisher=''La Croix''|date=23 October 2013|accessdate=3 May 2015|language=French}}</ref>
