{{Taoism}}

The '''''Zhuangzi''''' (<small>Mandarin:</small> {{IPAc-cmn|zh|uang|1|.|z|^|3}}; historically romanized '''''Chuang-tzu''''') is an ancient Chinese text from the late [[Warring States period]] (476{{ndash}}221{{sbc}}) which contains stories and anecdotes that exemplify the carefree nature of the ideal [[Daoist]] sage.  Named for its traditional author, "Master Zhuang" ([[Zhuang Zhou|Zhuangzi]]), the ''Zhuangzi'' is{{mdash}}along with the ''[[Tao Te Ching]]''{{mdash}}one of the two foundational texts of [[Daoism]], and is generally considered the most important of all Daoist writings.

The ''Zhuangzi'' consists of a large collection of anecdotes, allegories, parables, and fables, which are often humorous or irreverent in nature.  Its main themes are of spontaneity in action and of freedom from the human world and its conventions. The fables and anecdotes in the text attempt to illustrate the falseness of human distinctions between good and bad, large and small, life and death, and human and nature. While other ancient Chinese philosophers focused on moral and personal duty, Zhuangzi promoted carefree wandering and becoming one with "the Way" (''Dào'' 道) by following nature.

Though primarily known as a philosophical work, the ''Zhuangzi'' is regarded as one of the greatest literary works in all of Chinese history, and has been called "the most important pre-[[Qin dynasty|Qin]] text for the study of Chinese literature." A masterpiece of both philosophical and literary skill, it has significantly influenced writers for more than 2000 years from the [[Han dynasty]] (206{{sbc}}{{ndash}}AD{{nbsp}}220) to the present.  Many major Chinese writers and poets in history—such as [[Sima Xiangru]] and [[Sima Qian]] during the Han dynasty, [[Ruan Ji]] and [[Tao Yuanming]] during the [[Six Dynasties]] (222{{ndash}}589), [[Li Bai]] during the [[Tang dynasty]] (618{{ndash}}907), and [[Su Shi]] and [[Lu You]] in the [[Song dynasty]] (960{{ndash}}1279)—were heavily influenced by the ''Zhuangzi''.

==History==
===Authorship and textual history===
The ''Zhuangzi'' is named for and attributed to [[Zhuang Zhou]]{{mdash}}usually known as "Master Zhuang" ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: "Zhuangzi" 莊子){{mdash}}a man generally said to have been born around 369{{sbc}} at a place called Meng ({{lang|zh|蒙}}) in the [[Song (state)|state of Song]] (around modern [[Shangqiu]], [[Henan Province]]), and to have died around 301, 295, or 286{{sbc}}.{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=21}}{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xxxi}}{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=2314}}{{sfnp|Wilkinson|2015|p=697}} Almost nothing is concretely known of Zhuangzi's life.  He is thought to have spent time in the southern [[Chu (state)|state of Chu]], as well as in [[Ancient Linzi|Linzi]], the capital of the [[Qi (state)|state of Qi]].{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xxxi}} [[Sima Qian]]'s [[Records of the Grand Historian|''Records of the Grand Historian'' (''Shiji'' 史記)]], the first of China's [[Ershisi shi|24 dynastic histories]], has a biography of Zhuangzi, but most of it seems to have simply been drawn from anecdotes in the ''Zhuangzi'' itself.{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xxxi-xxxiii}} The American scholar and ''Zhuangzi'' translator [[Burton Watson]] noted, "Whoever Zhuang Zhou was, the writings attributed to him bear the stamp of a brilliant and original mind."{{sfnp|Watson|2003|p=3}}

Scholars have recognized since at least the [[Song dynasty]] (960{{ndash}}1279) that some parts of the book could not have been written by Zhuangzi himself.{{sfnp|Roth|1993|p=56}}  Since ancient times, however, its first seven chapters{{mdash}}the ''nèi piān'' 內篇 "inner chapters"{{mdash}}have been considered to be the actual work of Zhuangzi, and most modern scholars agree with this view.{{sfnp|Roth|1993|p=56}} How many, if any, of the remaining 26 chapters{{mdash}}the ''wài piān'' 外篇 "outer chapters" and ''zá piān'' 雜篇 "miscellaneous chapters"{{mdash}}were written by Zhuangzi has long been debated.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=2315}}  It is generally accepted that the middle and later ''Zhuangzi'' chapters are the result of a subsequent process of "accretion and redaction" by later authors "responding to the scintillating brilliance" of the inner chapters.{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=21}}  All of the 33 surviving chapters are accepted as compositions from the 4th to 2nd centuries BC.{{sfnp|Kern|2010|p=74}}

Details of the ''Zhuangzi''{{'}}s textual history prior to the [[Han dynasty]] (206{{sbc}}{{snd}}AD{{nbsp}}220) are largely unknown.  Traces of its influence in late [[Warring States period]] (475{{ndash}}221{{sbc}}) philosophical texts such as the ''[[Guanzi (text)|Guanzi]]'', ''[[Han Feizi (book)|Han Feizi]]'', ''[[Huainanzi]]'', and ''[[Lüshi Chunqiu]]'' suggest that Zhuangzi's intellectual lineage was already fairly influential in the states of [[Qi (state)|Qi]] and [[Chu (state)|Chu]] in the 3rd century{{sbc}}.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=33}} The ''Records of the Grand Historian'' refers to a 100,000-word ''Zhuangzi'' work and references several chapters that are still in the text.{{sfnp|Roth|1993|p=57}}  The [[Book of Han|''Book of Han'' (''Han shu'' 漢書)]], finished in AD 111, lists a ''Zhuangzi'' in 52 chapters, which many scholars believe to be the original form of the work.{{sfnp|Roth|1993|p=58}} A number of different forms of the ''Zhuangzi'' survived into the [[Tang dynasty]] (618{{ndash}}907), but a shorter and more popular 33-chapter form of the book prepared by the philosopher and writer [[Guo Xiang]] around AD 300 is the source of all surviving editions.{{sfnp|Roth|1993|p=58}} In 742, the ''Zhuangzi'' was canonized as one of the [[Chinese Classics]] by an imperial proclamation from [[Emperor Xuanzong of Tang]], which awarded it the honorific title ''True Scripture of Southern Florescence'' (''Nanhua zhenjing'' 南華真經),{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xxxi}} though most orthodox scholars did not consider the ''Zhuangzi'' to be a true "classic" (''jing'' {{lang|zh|經}}) due to its non-Confucian nature.{{sfnp|Goldin|2001|p=87}}

===Manuscripts===
[[File:Zhuangzi Tian Yun Ms.JPG|upright=1.1|thumb|Tang dynasty ''Zhuangzi'' manuscript preserved in Japan (1930s replica)]]

Portions of the ''Zhuangzi'' have been discovered among bamboo slip texts from Warring States period and [[Han dynasty]] tombs, particularly at the [[Shuanggudui]] and [[Zhangjiashan Han bamboo texts]] sites.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=2315}}  One of the slips from the [[Guodian Chu slips|Guodian bamboo texts]], which date to around 300 BC, contains what appears to be a short fragment from the "Ransacking Coffers" ("Qu qie" 胠篋) chapter.{{sfnp|Knechtges|2014|p=2315}}

A large number of ''Zhuangzi'' fragments dating from the early Tang dynasty were discovered among the [[Dunhuang manuscripts]] in the early 20th century by the expeditions of Hungarian-British explorer [[Aurel Stein]] and French Sinologist [[Paul Pelliot]].{{sfnp|Roth|1993|pp=61-62}} They collectively form about twelve chapters of Guo Xiang's version of the ''Zhuangzi'', and are preserved mostly at the [[British Library]] and the [[Bibliothèque Nationale de France]].{{sfnp|Roth|1993|p=62}} 

Among the Japanese national treasures preserved in the [[Kōzan-ji]] temple in [[Kyoto]] is a ''Zhuangzi'' manuscript from the [[Muromachi period]] (1338{{ndash}}1573).{{sfnp|Roth|1993|p=62}} The manuscript has seven complete chapters from the "outer" and "miscellaneous" chapters, and is believed to be a close copy of an annotated edition written in the 7th century by the Chinese [[Daoist]] master Cheng Xuanying (成玄英; fl. 630&ndash;660).{{sfnp|Roth|1993|p=62}}

==Content==
{{Asian philosophy sidebar}}
Almost all of the 33 surviving ''Zhuangzi'' chapters contain fables and allegories.{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=23}} Most ''Zhuangzi'' stories are fairly short and simple, such as "Lickety" and "Split" drilling seven holes in "[[Hundun|Wonton]]" (chapter 7) or Zhuangzi being discovered sitting and drumming on a basin after his wife dies (chapter 18), although a few are longer and more complex, like the story of Master Lie and the [[magus]] (chapter 14) and the account of the [[Yellow Emperor]]'s music (chapter 14).{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=23}} Unlike the other stories and allegories in other pre-[[Qin dynasty|Qin]] texts, the ''Zhuangzi'' is unique in that the allegories form the bulk of the text, rather than occasional features, and are always witty, emotional, and are not limited to reality.{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=23}}

Unlike other ancient Chinese works, whose allegories were usually based on historical legends and proverbs, most ''Zhuangzi'' stories seem to have been invented by Zhuangzi himself.  Some are completely whimsical, such as the strange description of evolution from "misty spray" through a series of substances and insects to horses and humans (chapter 18), while a few other passages seem to be "sheer playful nonsense" which read like [[Lewis Carroll]]'s "[[Jabberwocky]]".{{sfnp|Mair|1998|pp=23-24}} The ''Zhuangzi'' is full of quirky and fantastic characters, such as "Mad Stammerer", "Fancypants Scholar", "Sir Plow", and a man who believes his left arm will turn into a rooster, his right arm will turn into a crossbow, and his buttocks will become cartwheels.{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=24}}

A master of language, Zhuangzi sometimes engages in logic and reasoning, but then turns it upside down or carries the arguments to absurdity to demonstrate the limitations of human knowledge and the rational world.{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=24}} Some of Zhuangzi's reasoning, such as his renowned argument with his philosopher friend [[Hui Shi|Huizi]] (Master Hui) about the joy of fish (chapter 17), have been compared to the [[Socratic dialogue|Socratic]] and [[Plato|Platonic dialogue]] traditions, and Huizi's paradoxes near the end of the book have been termed "strikingly like those of [[Zeno of Elea]]."{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=24}}

