==Themes==
[[File:Zhuangzi.gif|right|upright=0.75|thumb|Zhuangzi as an old man]]
The stories and anecdotes of the ''Zhuangzi'' embody a unique set of principles and attitudes, including living one's life with natural spontaneity, uniting one's inner self with the cosmic "Way" (''Dao''), keeping oneself distant from politics and social obligations, accepting death as a natural transformation, showing appreciation and praise for things others view as useless or aimless, and stridently rejecting social values and conventional reasoning.{{sfnp|Kern|2010|p=74}}  These principles form the core ideas of philosophical [[Daoism]].{{sfnp|Kern|2010|p=74}}  The other major philosophical schools of ancient China{{mdash}}such as [[Confucianism]], [[Legalism (Chinese philosophy)|Legalism]], and [[Mohism]]{{mdash}}were all concerned with concrete social, political, or ethical reforms designed to reform people and society and thereby alleviate the problems and suffering of the world.{{sfnp|Watson|2003|p=3}} However, Zhuangzi believed that the key to true happiness was to free oneself from the world and its standards through the Daoist principle of  "inaction" ([[Wu wei|''wúwéi'' 無為]]){{mdash}}action that is not based on any purposeful striving or motives for gain{{mdash}}and was fundamentally opposed to systems that impose order on individuals.{{sfnp|Watson|2003|p=6}}{{sfnp|Kern|2010|p=75}}

The ''Zhuangzi'' interprets the universe as a thing that changes spontaneously without a conscious God or will driving it, and argues that humans can achieve ultimate happiness by living equally spontaneously.{{sfnp|Puett|2001|pp=76-77}} It argues that because of humans' advanced cognitive abilities, they have a tendency to create artificial distinctions{{mdash}}such as good versus bad, large versus small, usefulness versus uselessness, and social systems like Confucianism{{mdash}}that remove themselves from the natural spontaneity of the universe.{{sfnp|Puett|2001|p=77}} In order to illustrate the mindlessness and spontaneity he felt should characterize human action, Zhuangzi most frequently uses the analogy of craftsmen or artisans.{{sfnp|Watson|2003|p=6}} As Burton Watson described, "the skilled woodcarver, the skilled butcher, the skilled swimmer does not ponder or ratiocinate on the course of action he should take; his skill has become so much a part of him that he merely acts instinctively and spontaneously and, without knowing why, achieves success."{{sfnp|Watson|2003|p=6}} The term "wandering" (''yóu''{{nbsp}}遊) is used throughout the stories of the ''Zhuangzi'' to describe how an enlightened person "wanders through all of creation, enjoying its delights without ever becoming attached to any one part of it."{{sfnp|Watson|2003|p=6}}

The ''Zhuangzi'' vigorously opposes formal government, which Zhuangzi seems to have felt was problematic at its foundation "because of the opposition between man and nature."{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xli}} The text tries to show that "as soon as government intervenes in natural affairs, it destroys all possibility of genuine happiness."{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xlii}} It is unclear if Zhuangzi's positions were "tantamount to [[anarchy]], and he was by no means in favor of violence."{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xli}} The political references in the ''Zhuangzi'' are more concerned with what government should not do rather than what kind of government should exist.{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xli}}

Western scholars have long noticed that the ''Zhuangzi'' is often strongly anti-[[rationalism|rationalist]].  Mohism, deriving from Zhuangzi's possible contemporary [[Mozi]], was the most logically sophisticated school in ancient China.  Whereas reason and logic became the hallmark of [[Greek philosophy]] and then the entire Western philosophical tradition, in China philosophers preferred to rely on moral persuasion and intuition.{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xliii}} The ''Zhuangzi'' played a significant role in the traditional Chinese skepticism toward rationalism, as Zhuangzi frequently turns logical arguments upside-down to satirize and discredit them.  However, Zhuangzi did not entirely abandon language and reason, but "only wished to point out that overdependence on them could limit the flexibility of thought."{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xliii}}

==Influence==
The ''Zhuangzi'' is by far the most influential purely-literary work dating from before China's imperial unification in 221{{sbc}}.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=30}} Its literary quality, imagination and creativity, and linguistic prowess were entirely unprecedented in the period of its creation.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=30}} Virtually every major Chinese writer or poet in history, from [[Sima Xiangru]] and [[Sima Qian]] during the [[Han dynasty]], [[Ruan Ji]] and [[Tao Yuanming]] during the [[Six Dynasties]], [[Li Bai]] during the [[Tang dynasty]], to [[Su Shi]] and [[Lu You]] in the [[Song dynasty]] were "deeply imbued with the ideas and artistry of the ''Zhuangzi''."{{sfnp|Mair|1998|pp=22-23}}

===Early times===
Traces of the ''Zhuangzi''{{'}}s influence in late Warring States period philosophical texts such as the ''[[Guanzi (text)|Guanzi]]'', ''[[Han Feizi (book)|Han Feizi]]'', ''[[Huainanzi]]'', and ''[[Lüshi Chunqiu]]'' suggest that Zhuangzi's intellectual lineage was already fairly influential in the states of [[Qi (state)|Qi]] and [[Chu (state)|Chu]] in the 3rd century{{sbc}}.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=33}}  However, during the [[Qin dynasty|Qin]] and [[Han dynasty|Han dynasties]]{{mdash}}with their state-sponsored [[Legalism (Chinese philosophy)|Legalist]] and [[Confucianism|Confucian]] ideologies, respectively{{mdash}}the ''Zhuangzi'' does not seem to have been highly regarded.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=33}}   One exception is Han dynasty scholar [[Jia Yi]]'s 170{{sbc}} work "''Fu'' on the Owl" (''Fúniǎo fù'' {{lang|zh|鵩鳥賦}}), the earliest definitively known [[fu (poetry)|''fu'' rhapsody]], which does not reference the ''Zhuangzi'' by name but cites it for one-sixth of the poem.{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=22}}

After the collapse of the Han dynasty in AD 207 and the subsequent chaos of the [[Three Kingdoms period]], both the ''Zhuangzi'' and Zhuang Zhou began to rise in popularity and acclaim.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=33}}  The 3rd century AD poets [[Ruan Ji]] and [[Xi Kang]], both members of the famous [[Seven Worthies of the Bamboo Grove]], were ardent ''Zhuangzi'' admirers,{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=34}} and one of Ruan's essays, entitled "Discourse on Summing Up the ''Zhuangzi''" (''Dá Zhuāng lùn'' 達莊論), is still extant.{{sfnp|Mair|1998|p=23}}  This period saw Confucianism temporarily surpassed by a revival of Daoism and old divination texts, such as the [[I Ching|''Classic of Changes'' (''I Ching'' 易經)]], and many early medieval Chinese poets, artists, and calligraphers were deeply influenced by the ''Zhuangzi''.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=34}}

===Daoism and Buddhism===
The ''Zhuangzi'' has been called "the most important of all the Daoist writings",{{sfnp|Idema|Haft|1997|p=90}} and its "inner chapters" embody the core ideas of philosophical [[Daoism]].{{sfnp|Kern|2010|p=74}} In the 4th century AD, the ''Zhuangzi'' became a major source of imagery and terminology for a new form of Daoism known as the [[Shangqing School|"Highest Clarity" (''Shangqing'' 上清)]] school that was popular among the aristocracy of the [[Jin dynasty (265-420)|Jin dynasty]] (AD 265{{ndash}}420).  Highest Clarity Daoism borrowed notable ''Zhuangzi'' terms, such as "perfected man" (''zhēn rén'' {{lang|zh|真人}}), "Great Clarity" (''Tài Qīng'' {{lang|zh|太清}}), and "fasting the mind" (''xīn zhāi'' {{lang|zh|心齋}}), and though they are used somewhat differently than in the ''Zhuangzi'' itself, they still show the important role the ''Zhuangzi'' played at the time.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=34}}

The ''Zhuangzi'' was very influential in the adaptation of [[Buddhism]] to Chinese culture after Buddhism was first brought to China from [[India]] in the 1st century AD.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=34}} [[Zhi Dun]], China's first aristocratic Buddhist monk, wrote a prominent commentary to the ''Zhuangzi'' in the mid-4th century.{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=34}}  The ''Zhuangzi'' also played a significant role in the formation of [[Zen Buddhism|Chan ("Zen") Buddhism]], which grew out of "a fusion of Buddhist ideology and ancient Daoist thought."{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=34}}  Among the traits Chan/Zen Buddhism borrowed from the ''Zhuangzi'' are a distrust of language and logic, an insistence that "the Dao" can be found in everything, even dung and urine, and a fondness for dialogues based on riddles or paradigm-challenging statements known as ''gōng'àn'' ({{lang|zh|公案}}; Japanese ''[[kōan]]'').{{sfnp|Mair|2000|p=34}}

===Medieval and early modern===
The ''Zhuangzi'' retained prominence throughout Chinese history as the preeminent example of core Daoist philosophical ideals.  The 17th century scholar [[Gu Yanwu]] lamented his government's flippant use of the ''Zhuangzi'' on the [[keju|imperial examination]] essays as representative of a decline in traditional morals at the end of the [[Ming dynasty]] (1368–1644).{{sfnp|Li|2010|pp=158–59}}  In the great Chinese novel [[Dream of the Red Chamber|''Dream of the Red Chamber'' (''Hong lou meng'' 紅樓夢)]], the main protagonist, Jia Baoyu, often turns to the ''Zhuangzi'' for comfort amidst his despair over conflicting love interests and relationships.{{sfnp|Shang|2010|p=290}}  The story of Zhuangzi drumming on a tub and singing after the death of his wife inspired an entire tradition of folk music called "funeral drumming" (''sàng-gǔ'' {{lang|zh|喪鼓}}) in central China's [[Hubei]] and [[Hunan]] Provinces that survived into the 18th and 19th centuries.{{sfnp|Idema|2010|p=403}}

===Modern===
Outside of China and the traditional "[[Sinosphere]]", the ''Zhuangzi'' lags far behind the ''[[Tao Te Ching]]'' in general popularity, and is rarely known by non-scholars.{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xlii}} A number of prominent scholars have attempted to bring the ''Zhuangzi'' to wider attention among Western readers.  In 1939, the British translator and Sinologist [[Arthur Waley]] described the ''Zhuangzi'' as "one of the most entertaining as well as one of the profoundest books in the world."<ref>Cited in {{Harvp|Graham|1981|p=3}}.</ref>  In the introduction to his 1994 translation of the ''Zhuangzi'', the American [[Sinology|Sinologist]] [[Victor H. Mair]] wrote: "I feel a sense of injustice that the ''Dao De Jing'' is so well known to my fellow citizens while the ''Zhuangzi'' is so thoroughly ignored, because I firmly believe that the latter is in every respect a superior work."{{sfnp|Mair|1994|p=xliii}}

